  "learnings_before": "- Both valproate and carbamazepine are guideline‑consistent first‑line options for focal seizures in children ≤ 2 years; selection is guided by drug availability, tolerability, and the need for laboratory monitoring.\n- Aromatic AEDs (carbamazepine, lamotrigine, phenytoin) are acceptable for focal epilepsy but must be avoided in any child with a documented drug‑induced rash or hypersensitivity.\n- Before any change of therapy, clinicians must obtain baseline safety labs (ALT/AST < 2 × ULN, platelet count > 150 × 10⁹/L, ammonia within normal limits) and, when feasible, a serum level of the current AED.\n- Dose optimisation is performed first: if the current dose is < 20 mg/kg/day for valproate or < 15 mg/kg/day for carbamazepine and seizure control is suboptimal, the dose should be titrated upward in 25‑50 mg increments every 1–2 weeks before considering drug substitution or adjuncts.\n- Exaggerated startles, feeding difficulty, or increased tone in children with cerebral palsy are not automatically attributed to drug toxicity; they require confirmation (e.g., seizure diary or video‑EEG) before altering the regimen.\n- The decision hierarchy is: (1) confirm seizure‑free status (≥ 6 months) and adherence ≥ 80 %; (2) verify normal safety labs; (3) maintain the current regimen unchanged; (4) if either seizure control or labs are inadequate, proceed to dose optimisation; (5) if optimisation fails, consider switching to valproate (after normal LFTs) or adding levetiracetam as an adjunct.\n- Valproate is stocked in >90 % of district pharmacies at ≈ $0.08 per 100 mg; carbamazepine is similarly stocked at ≈ $0.05 per 100 mg; levetiracetam is 2–3 × more expensive and often unavailable, so it is reserved for documented valproate intolerance or failure.\n- Phenobarbital is reserved for refractory cases or when both valproate and levetiracetam are unavailable; it may be used in spastic cerebral palsy only with close monitoring for sedation, otherwise it is avoided.\n- Initiation of valproate requires baseline liver function tests and ammonia; if ALT/AST > 2 × ULN or ammonia is elevated, valproate should be deferred and an alternative AED chosen.\n- When a child is seizure‑free on a stable valproate dose within the therapeutic window (20–30 mg/kg/day) and safety labs are normal, the protocol mandates continuation of the exact current dose without escalation or adjunct addition.",
  "candidate_learnings": "- Core essential medicine for focal seizures in children ≤2 years is carbamazepine (first‑line); phenobarbital is second‑line; valproate is a secondary essential used only when carbamazepine is contraindicated; levetiracetam is non‑essential and used only in donor‑sponsored programs.\n- Decision rule: IF focal seizure AND age ≤2 y AND no documented rash or hypersensitivity → prescribe carbamazepine; ELSE IF carbamazepine contraindicated → prescribe valproate after normal LFTs and ammonia; ELSE → prescribe phenobarbital.\n- Carbamazepine dosing: start 5 mg/kg/day divided BID, titrate by 5 mg/kg/day every 2 weeks to target 10–15 mg/kg/day (max 30 mg/kg/day); obtain serum carbamazepine level at week 2 if breakthrough seizures persist.\n- Baseline labs required before any aromatic AED (carbamazepine, phenobarbital, phenytoin): CBC, ALT/AST, serum sodium; repeat CBC and sodium at week 2 and month 1.\n- Valproate dosing: start 20 mg/kg/day divided BID, increase to 30 mg/kg/day if needed; obtain baseline liver function tests and ammonia, repeat LFTs at 2 weeks.\n- Drug availability and cost in Ugandan district pharmacies: carbamazepine stocked >90 % of the time, ≈ $0.05 per 100 mg; valproate stocked >80 % of the time, ≈ $0.08 per 100 mg; levetiracetam stocked <20 % of the time, costing 2–3 × more than valproate.\n- Cost‑driven hierarchy: prioritize core essential (carbamazepine) over secondary (valproate) and non‑essential (levetiracetam) when efficacy and safety are acceptable.\n- Common adverse events with carbamazepine in Ugandan children: rash, hyponatraemia, neutropenia; monitor CBC and serum sodium accordingly.\n- In children with cerebral palsy, increased tone or feeding difficulty is not automatically attributed to drug toxicity; adjust medication only if lab abnormalities are documented.\n- HIV status consideration: if the child is HIV‑positive or receiving efavirenz, avoid carbamazepine due to heightened rash risk and choose valproate instead.\n- Valproate + carbamazepine combination is reserved for females approaching menarche to exploit carbamazepine‑induced enzyme induction and reduce valproate exposure; requires serum valproate level monitoring after carbamazepine initiation.\n- Levetiracetam as adjunct is considered only after documented valproate failure or intolerance and when a reliable supply chain is confirmed.\n- Adherence requirement: medication adherence must be ≥80 % (assessed by caregiver interview or pill count) before any dose change, drug switch, or adjunct addition.",
  "rejected_learnings": "- Core essential medicine for focal seizures in children ≤2 years is carbamazepine (first‑line); phenobarbital is second‑line; valproate is a secondary essential used only when carbamazepine is contraindicated; levetiracetam is non‑essential and used only in donor‑sponsored programs.\n- Decision rule: IF focal seizure AND age ≤2 y AND no documented rash or hypersensitivity → prescribe carbamazepine; ELSE IF carbamazepine contraindicated → prescribe valproate after normal LFTs and ammonia; ELSE → prescribe phenobarbital.\n- Carbamazepine dosing: start 5 mg/kg/day divided BID, titrate by 5 mg/kg/day every 2 weeks to target 10–15 mg/kg/day (max 30 mg/kg/day); obtain serum carbamazepine level at week 2 if breakthrough seizures persist.\n- Baseline labs required before any aromatic AED (carbamazepine, phenobarbital, phenytoin): CBC, ALT/AST, serum sodium; repeat CBC and sodium at week 2 and month 1.\n- Valproate dosing: start 20 mg/kg/day divided BID, increase to 30 mg/kg/day if needed; obtain baseline liver function tests and ammonia, repeat LFTs at 2 weeks.\n- Drug availability and cost in Ugandan district pharmacies: carbamazepine stocked >90 % of the time, ≈ $0.05 per 100 mg; valproate stocked >80 % of the time, ≈ $0.08 per 100 mg; levetiracetam stocked <20 % of the time, costing 2–3 × more than valproate.\n- Cost‑driven hierarchy: prioritize core essential (carbamazepine) over secondary (valproate) and non‑essential (levetiracetam) when efficacy and safety are acceptable.\n- Common adverse events with carbamazepine in Ugandan children: rash, hyponatraemia, neutropenia; monitor CBC and serum sodium accordingly.\n- In children with cerebral palsy, increased tone or feeding difficulty is not automatically attributed to drug toxicity; adjust medication only if lab abnormalities are documented.\n- HIV status consideration: if the child is HIV‑positive or receiving efavirenz, avoid carbamazepine due to heightened rash risk and choose valproate instead.\n- Valproate + carbamazepine combination is reserved for females approaching menarche to exploit carbamazepine‑induced enzyme induction and reduce valproate exposure; requires serum valproate level monitoring after carbamazepine initiation.\n- Levetiracetam as adjunct is considered only after documented valproate failure or intolerance and when a reliable supply chain is confirmed.\n- Adherence requirement: medication adherence must be ≥80 % (assessed by caregiver interview or pill count) before any dose change, drug switch, or adjunct addition.",
